A hierarchical clustering is applied to the 10 observations in Table 4 using maximum linkage, and the result is shown in Figure 6 (a dendrogram). Which one of the following set of clusters cannot be obtained from the dendrogram by applying a valid cutoff?

A. {o3, o10, o2, o5}, {o1, o4}, {o8, o9}, {o6, o7}
B. {o3, o10, o2}, {o5}, {o1, o4}, {o8, o9}, {o6, o7}
C. {o3, o10}, {o2}, {o5}, {o1, o4}, {o8, o9}, {o6, o7}
D. {o3, o10}, {o2}, {o5}, {o1}, {o4}, {o8, o9}, {o6, o7}

We again consider the Palmer Penguins dataset and the N = 10 observations in Table 5. The data is processed to produce four new binary features such that fi = 1 corresponds to xi greater than the median, giving the N x M = 10 x 4 binary matrix in Table 5 (attribute x5 is not considered here). The matrix can be considered as representing N = 10 transactions o11, o12, ..., o20 and M = 4 items f1, f2, ..., f4. Which of the following options represents all (non-empty) itemsets with support greater than 0.25 (and only itemsets with support greater than 0.25)?

A. {f1}, {f3}, {f1,f3}
B. {f1}, {f2}, {f3}, {f4}, {f1,f3}
C. {f1}, {f2}, {f3}, {f4}, {f1,f3}, {f1,f4}, {f3,f4}, {f1,f3,f4}
D. {f1}, {f3}
